node.text:
We are beyond excited to announce the launch of our first MALDIVES expeditions!

You will be fully accommodated with 3 Dives per day to encounter Tresher Sharks, Tiger Sharks, Whale Sharks and Mantas, food and Non Alcoholic drinks, also your participation will support local businesses and ocean conservation organizations! The expedition will be broadcast live on @discoversharks 🎥Click the link in our bio for more details 
📧: DM your email address to @discoversharkstours if you’re ready to book your spot!
Video by @tannerunderwater

node.text: This is the most tragic thing I’ve ever filmed: a pod of dolphins swimming through a giant oil spill. The spill is spanning an area covering more than 50 miles, and it is lurking just off the coast of San Diego. On today’s extended trip we made our way to our reliable Blue Whale hotspot near San Clemente Island and we were shocked when the whales seemingly vanished. Just 24 hours earlier this zone was full of the feeding giants. It was then that we began making our way south, and soon made this shocking discovery. Tragic doesn’t begin to cover it. For more than 50 miles the ocean was covered in a thick sheen of oil, a devastating tragedy for the environment. We know very little at this time, and we are trying to make these images go viral in hopes of getting some answers as to how this happened. More shocking yet, 70+ miles away back in coastal San Diego, the local whale watching boats reported an area thick with oil encroaching on the local waters as well. I truly hope this isn’t as bad as it appears, but if this oil is already in an area that spans at a minimum of 70 miles, we could have a catastrophe of unimaginable scale on our hands. Please share this video with your followers and tag people, celebrities, influencers and news media that need to see and share it too: WE NEED ANSWERS BEFORE ANY MORE MARINE LIFE SUFFERS! We’ve reached out to NOAA, the Coast Guard, and the EPA. We hope to have an update soon. Video and caption by our friend @dolphindronedom #saveouroceans

PLEASE TAKE ACTION NOW! A seemingly small action today really will help make a historical change to HELP SAVE SHARKS in Hawaii! We’ve been pretty quiet about this on social media til this point but it is now the FINAL step to getting sharks fully protected in Hawaii! 

Please lend them your voice by writing into to the Governor of Hawaii today via the link in the bio @oneoceanconservation and ask him to : “PROTECT SHARKS by please SUPPORTING and signing HB553 into law.”

The link is in the bio of @oneoceanconservation 

and I have a good feeling this is the year that manō (sharks) in Hawaii get the protection that they need, deserve, and traditionally were given. Lets protect sharks everywhere we can and for me it’s significant to see the manō I have grown up with (who have taught me so much) get protection from purposeful killing, capture, entanglement, and harm. 

Video of Roxy, I’m grateful she seems to visit me around my birthday, the holidays, and when she needs debris like this net and fishing line removed. This law will help to reduce nets in shark nursery habitats (nets like the ones we’ve cut off her several times) and hopefully save other sharks from broken jaws like hers as it will be a fineable offense to purposely (not accidentally) capture or kill a shark. This law won’t criminalize accidental capture, but it will mean that fisherman must let a shark go if they realize they do accidentally capture a shark, which responsible fishermen already do. 

LINK IN BIO @OneOceanConservation PLEASE SUPPORT THE PROTECTION OF SHARKS TODAY. Mahalo nui loa. Malamamano Respect and protect sharks. 
Special thanks to the many organizations, individuals, reps, and senators who have been helping support this bill all along the way and for many years now. #ForManō #HelpSaveSharks #protectsharks #SaveTheOcean

Only recently sharks have started to come back to some areas and if they allow it to happen again sharks will be gone in just a matter of few months. Lets pressure the government to stop this. A saltie (saltwater crocodile) uses his buddy to demonstrate a perfect deathroll for the humans in attendance.

I'm not sure what the guy with the paddle was attempting to accomplish, but this footage also features a guy with a paddle.

Here's something I didn't know until 8 minutes ago: There are more crocodiles residing in Australia's Northern Territory than anywhere else in the world.

node.text:
Happy international women’s day / Thank you @pelagicdivefuvahmulah for inviting me to your tiger shark island #paradise and this was so exciting to be a part of taking the first local woman from #fuvamulah island to snorkel with tiger sharks out in the #pelagic deep open ocean. We have a new #LadyShark 💕🦈💕 I have always actively supported women in science, conservation, environmental causes, and diving is such a great way to inspire that for men and women alike, not to mention it’s good for your physical and mental well-being 💙 Thank you to @pelagicdivefuvahmulah for empowering women and facilitating programs in the local and international community and thank you to my new Seaster featured here: @anshooda 💞🥰 for volunteering, she says life on land is boring in comparison to this 💕🦈💕 This was her first time snorkeling and first time seeing a shark.
#InternationalWomensDay #StrongWomen #Seasters #LadySharks 

Filmed by my love: @juansharks 😘
#Maldives @oneoceanglobal #beautifulmaldives #womendiving #womenwhodive

Post from 2020 / #repost 😭💙👉@jklamlam This week marks 50 years since the Penn Cove orcas were stolen from their home in the wild and sold into captivity. Lolita is the last remaining orca alive out of that group. She’s been swimming in circles for decades in an extremely tiny tank at the Miami Seaquarium. Does this look like enough space for an animal who could swim up to 140 miles a day in the wild? She can barely swim in a straight line! How can people be ok with this?? She deserves to be released to a seaside sanctuary. Next time you complain about quarantine, imagine swimming in circles for 50 years😢 #FreeLolita CHECK OUT THE LINK IN @peta’s bio to take action! 
Shared via @protect.animals.worldwide

Save the Dates: 
Sep 9th - 16th 
spend 4 full days in the ocean exploring the wonders of South Ari Atoll where you’ll encounter The Giant Mantas and Whale Sharks in pristine clear Blue water, and of course many other ocean creatures!
Whats included? 
-Breakfast, Lunch and Dinner
- Transportation
- Accommodation in Dhigurah 🏝 
- 6 Full Days in the Ocean

node.text: Words by @tannerunderwater RIP Mike D, @reefhunter - I got this shot dedicated to you on the day we celebrated your life as we drifted deep ledge, the place you called home. Before I had ever done any work with sharks I used to show people your photos, and I would say THIS is what I want to do. I love that your career started with Florida shark diving. When I first started working here I would think of the limitless possibilities this job would give me considering what you had accomplished. You will never know how much you inspired me. Life can be so painful, I know you’re in a better place. As your family spread your ashes into the ocean I couldn’t help but feel like it isn’t over. Your legacy will live on, whether with us or in spirit in the ocean. I hope one day people can say the same about me. Rest easy, from one of the many people your work inspired. 💙🦈

words by @gabovlzqz
All the people who dedicate their lives to the sea are in the front row to experience the amazing shows that marine life has to offer, but we also experience the negative side and we have to see the impact that humans have on these animals and our planet.

 This was recorded one 2 days after the shark fishing ban ended (May-June). Just got in the water to document what happened without touching the buoy or the dead shark.
 As I start to swim towards the boat I see another silky shark swimming from the depths approaching me and seeing it swimming next to the dead shark was hard, to think that maybe tomorrow won't be alive  is difficult and frustrating. 😔

 It's not the first dead shark I've seen and it definitely won't be the last either.  I've been lucky to see big groups of hundreds of sharks and swimming with them, and seeing them die is not easy at all, and I feel  pain and anger to see how the animals that I love so much are getting killed every minute. 
I spend most of my days doing what I love and swimming with sharks and seeing how fascinating they are is a privilege that not everyone can have.

As long as there is demand shark fishing will continue, fishermen are trying to survive and feed their families, not everyone likes to kill sharks and some are open to new opportunities.  What we can do to help these animals is to try to be more conscious with our food consumption, supporting petitions and organizations that are dedicated to protecting these species, by doing ecotourism we can help the local economy by giving them another source of income to these captains and fishermen, these animals are worth more alive than dead.  I'm not here to promote a tour of mine or any company with this post, but to raise awareness and showing what these animals suffer on their daily basis, we must all collaborate together, support and protect the animals that we all love.
